Serotonin antagonist and reuptake inhibitor (SARI)
- Trazodone

#ACE inhibitor: lower high blood pressure
Benazepril
Captopril
Enalapril
Lisinopril
Ramipril

#ARB: high blood pressure, block angiotensin receptor
Irbesartan
Losartan
Valsartan

#Beta blocker: manage arrhytmia and high blood pressure, block receptors for adrenaline and noradrenaline
Nonselective
- Labetalol
- Pindolol
- Propranolol
Selective
- Acebutolol
- Atenolol
- Bisoprolol
- Esmolol
- Metoprolol
- Nebivolol

#Corticosteroid
Glucocorticoid: bind to glucocorticoid receptor
- Prednisone: decrease inflammation
Mineralocorticoid: bind to mineralocorticoid receptor

#Antiulcer: against reflux
Omeprazole: proton pump inhibitor
Pantoprazole: proton pump inhibitor
H2 blocker: block histamine receptors in stomach
- Ranitidine: decrease stomach acid production

#Antihistamine
Cetirizine
Promethazine

#Antiasthmatic
Epinephrine/adrenaline: anaphylaxis, cardiac arrest
Budesonide (Pulmicort)
Montelukast (Singulair)
Salbutamol (Ventolin)
Tiotropium (Spiriva)

#Analgesic: pain relievers
Non-opioid
- Paracetamol (Panadol): antipyretic (overdose ~5g: liver failure)
- Ibuprofen (Nurofen): anti-inflammatory
- Aspirin: anti-inflammatory (overdose ~10g: brain/lungs edema)
- Naproxen (Aleve): anti-inflammatory
Opioid
- Morphine: recreational drug, found in opium, addictive
- Codeine: prodrug of morphine, found in opium
- Heroin: recreational drug, addictive
- Fentanyl: very strong, addictive

#Anesthetic: block nerve receptors, unconsciousness when general
General via inhalation
- Nitrous oxide
- Isoflurane
- Halothane
- Sevoflurane
General
- Ketamine
- Propofol: intravenous
- Thiopental: intravenous
Local: blocks sodium channels on neuron membrane
- Lidocaine
- Benzocaine
- Bupivacaine

